		<header>
			
			<h1>The dairy sector and the EUâ€™s evolving safety net policy  </h1>

			
			<h4>
												28 November 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The EC argues that â€˜the large number of uncertainties and risks surrounding market prospects ... highlight the need for an effective safety net as well as risk management instruments.â€™ Specifically, the EC impact assessment of its CAP reform proposals, and published alongside, argues that â€˜the experience of the 2008-09 dairy crisis demonstrated â€¦ the need to maintain an effective safety-net mechanismâ€™, but within a policy framework that promotes the more efficient use of the available policy tools.</p><p>Central to the EUâ€™s â€˜safety-netâ€™ policy remains the system of direct aid payments, which provides â€˜a cushion against income volatilityâ€™. This is supplemented by the use of a range of market stabilisation tools including: aid for private storage; intervention buying; disposal programmes; export refund support. It is felt that the use of these tools needs to be made more systematic, with their use being tailored to â€˜the specific needs of each sectorâ€™. The aim of this refocused safety-net policy is to minimise the use of such policy tools â€˜under normal market conditionsâ€™, while allowing â€˜the EU to act faster and more efficientlyâ€™ where exceptional market conditions arise.</p><p>With the likelihood of increased price volatility in the medium term, and in order to facilitate swift and effective intervention across all sectors where it might prove necessary, an additional safety net instrument has been created: the â‚¬3.5 billion emergency reserve (2014â€“2020) (see <i>Agritrade</i> article â€˜
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/CAP-reform/Multi-annual-budget-framework-sets-scene-for-CAP-reform-proposals" target="_blank">Multi-annual budget framework sets scene for CAP reform proposals</a>â€™, September 2011). Funds from this facility would be made available in response to â€˜exceptional circumstancesâ€™, and would finance the kind of emergency measures implemented in the dairy sector in 2009 (see <i>Agritrade</i> article â€˜
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/Policy-tools-critical-to-turning-around-crisis-in-the-EU-dairy-sector" target="_blank">Policy tools critical to turning around crisis in the EU dairy sector</a>â€™, May 2010).</p><p>The new EU policy focus on providing effective â€˜safety netsâ€™ has seen the elaboration of a number of new policy tools including:</p>
<ul>

<li>proposals for the promotion of risk management tools; </li>

<li>proposals for insurance schemes; </li>

<li>proposals for the establishment of mutual funds and </li>

<li>the development of policies to strengthen the functioning of food supply chains. </li>

</ul>
<p>With regard to the functioning of supply chains, the EC impact assessment annex on market measures notes that â€˜the dairy crisis â€¦ raised awareness of the significant tensions in contractual relations between actors of the chain and the lack of price transparency along the chain.â€™ Against this background, in the dairy sector the EUâ€™s emerging policy on strengthening the functioning of supply chains has focused on strengthening producer organisations, promoting transparency of contractual relationships and encouraging collaboration to foster innovation and ensure competition within the dairy sector.</p><p>Under the CAP reform proposals, this is being further elaborated, with three options under consideration:</p>
<ul>

<li><b>flexible cooperation</b> â€“ involving widening the range of cooperation allowed to producers and promoting best practice as regards the use of voluntary standards supply contracts; </li>

<li><b>enhanced cooperation</b> â€“ involving strengthening inter-branch organisation and producer organisation based on the experience in the fruit and vegetable sector; </li>

<li><b>regulated cooperation</b> â€“ involving the establishment of obligations to provide suppliers with written contracts and extending to derogations from the prohibition on price fixing.&nbsp;</li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>EC, â€˜Impact assessment: Common agricultural policy towards 2020â€™, SEC(2011) 1153, Commission Staff Working Paper, full text </p><p>
<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/analysis/perspec/cap-2020/impact-assessment/full-text_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/analysis/perspec/cap-2020/impact-assessm...</a></p><p>EC, â€˜Impact assessment: Common agricultural policy towards 2020â€™, Commission Staff Working Paper, Annex 5 - Market Measures, draft, 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/analysis/perspec/cap-2020/impact-assessment/annex5_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/analysis/perspec/cap-2020/impact-assessm...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>In the face of heightened price volatility and the growing gap between input cost increases and agricultural commodity price increases, the EUâ€™s new â‚¬3.5 billion emergency facility will finance the types of emergency measure seen in the dairy sector in 2009. Of particular concern have been the potential adjustment displacement effects of the expansion of purchases into, and subsequent sales from, intervention stocks. According to a USDA review of the EU dairy sector, the expansion of intervention buying for skimmed-milk powder (SMP), from the nominal ceiling of 109,000 tonnes to 282,587 tonnes, subsequently saw a major surge in EU exports of SMP in 2010 (+63%) (see <i>Agritrade</i> article, â€˜
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/USDA-review-of-EU-dairy-sector-development" target="_blank">USDA review of EU dairy sector development</a>â€™, July 2011). A more detailed analysis subsequently showed that milk powder exports to sub-Saharan African markets had increased by 62%, with fully 74.3% of these exports destined for Nigeria (+69%) and Ghana (+72%).</p><p>Potentially the availability of increased volumes of SMP could disrupt developing supply relationships between local milk producers and local dairy processing companies, significantly reducing farm gate prices for milk. Indeed, a dedicated dairy sector workshop in West Africa in 2010 called not only for greater investment in developing the production and marketing of milk, but also for the regulation of the flow of milk powder and other dairy imports, in line with national milk sector development strategies (see <i>Agritrade</i> article â€˜
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/Developing-a-value-added-dairy-sector-in-West-Africa" target="_blank">Developing a value-added dairy sector in West Africa</a>â€™, May 2011).</p><p>It is this type of external effect of the use of CAP policy tools that needs to be subject to careful monitoring and evaluation, with efforts being made to use existing EU policy tools in ways that avoid adverse consequences for emerging ACP dairy farming sectors.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
